Analysis of Impact of Military size on Global Peace Index

Cheolhong Ahn

Introduction¶

"The war to end all wars" is a famous term for the First World War of 1914-1918. However, history knows how that turned out. Soon after World War II engulfing entire Eruope in War. When World world II ended and the entire world saw the devastating power of nuclear bomb, some believed that human kind would not bring themselves to destruction and finally peace is about. However, we know from past that this lead to competition in cold war and today continues to threat wolrd peace by countries such as North Korea.

United States spend exorbitant amount of money on military and many believe that that strong military force is the only thing that can detterr conflict. Is this true? We will find out using Global Peace index and various military data such as military expenditure, army personnel count to see how these impact peace index of a country.

What is GPI?¶

Global Peace Index (GPI) is a report produced by the Institute for Economics & Peace (IEP) which measures the relative position of nations' and regions' peacefulness. The Index was first launched in May 2009 and since have quickly gained position as leading measure of peace. For furthur reading on GPI click Here

What we'll Accomplish in This tutorial¶

Thorughout This tutorial we will Process Data such as formatting dataframes as we like and imputing missing values, Make graph visualization of the data, build linear regressions models using dataframe and analyze and make a meaningful conclusion from obtained information.

Notice that while the military Data is not yearly but GPI and GDP expenditure are.

We will only use 2018 data as it is most recent data that exists for GDP and GPI and expenditure data. We'll also rename the year columns

We will then Merge the dataframes. We're intersted in Military power on global piece index so we will merge left on country names with gpi on left and other dataframes on right as we are only interested in countries that are ranked in gpi.

We have Missing data for military on Merge. By looking at the differences of the sets. We notice that while some are Indeed not matching due to missing countries, some are just due to different way to write the same country name. For example, in military dataframe, its "People's Republic of China" while its just "China" in GPI dataset. Luckily, its not many, so we'll just manually add them.

#changing names on mil to match the ones on GPI for merge
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "People's Republic of China", "Country"] = "China"
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "Côte d'Ivoire", "Country"] = "Cote d'Ivoire"
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "Czech Republic", "Country"] = "Czechia"
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "Kyrgyzstan", "Country"] = "Kyrgyz Republic"
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "Taiwan (Republic of China)", "Country"] = "Taiwan"
mil.loc[mil['Country'] == "Gambia", "Country"] = "The Gambia"

df = pd.merge(gpi, mil, on='Country', how='left')

df

Imputations¶

We finally have all the datasets merged into one. However, after inspecting the dataframe, we find out that there are missing data! We need to deal with this missing data.

Imputations are process of replacing missing data with substituted values. There are several ways that imputation can done and some do fit better in certain situation than the other. To read more about imputations. Click HERE

Cold-deck imputation is one of such method. Cold-deck imputation borrows variable data from similar input. For our dataset, it is hard to justify Cold-deck method for GPD and military expenditure as there are too many facotors that go into countrys' gdp and military expenditure that finding similar donor will be a big analysis on its own.

Regression imputation uses regression to predict missing value based on other variables. As such, it is dependent on relationship to other variables. However, We also cannot use regression for imputation at this point as we don't know if there are any relation between these variables yet (thats what we're trying to analzye!).

We will Use mean Imputation which takes mean value of the column for all missing data in a column. Downside of this method is that there is guaranteed to be no relationship between the imputed variable and any other measured variables but our data barely has missing data so the impact will be minimal.

In [390]:
df['GDP'] = df['GDP'].fillna(df['GDP'].mean())
df['Military_Expenditure'] = df['Military_Expenditure'].fillna(df['Military_Expenditure'].mean())
df['Active_military']= df['Active_military'].fillna(df['Active_military'].mean())
df['Reserve_military'] = df['Reserve_military'].fillna(df['Reserve_military'].mean())
df['Paramilitary'] = df['Paramilitary'].fillna(df['Paramilitary'].mean())
df['Total']= df['Total'].fillna(df['Total'].mean())
df['Per1000capita_active'] = df['Per1000capita_active'].fillna(df['Per1000capita_active'].mean())
df['Per1000capita_total'] = df['Per1000capita_total'].fillna(df['Per1000capita_total'].mean())

df = df.sort_values(by=['GPI_rank'])
df

From looking at the regression analysis, we get the probability of f-statisctic to be near 0 value. There is almost no chance that null hyphothesis of no relationship hold.

Next, we will use RANSAC to model regression. We saw from bar graph that there are some significant outliers in the data. Random sample consensus, or RANSAC, is an iterative method for estimating a mathematical model from a data set that contains outliers. The RANSAC algorithm works by identifying the outliers in a data set and estimating the desired model using data that does not contain outliers. To read furthur on RANSAC. Click Here

In [395]:
model_ransac = RANSACRegressor(residual_threshold=20000000000)
model_ransac.fit(x, y)
inlier_mask = model_ransac.inlier_mask_
outlier_mask = np.logical_not(inlier_mask)

# Predict data of estimated models
ransac_pred = model_ransac.predict(x)




plt.plot(x[inlier_mask], y[inlier_mask], '.g', label='Inliers')
plt.plot(x[outlier_mask], y[outlier_mask], '.r', label='Outliers')
plt.plot(x, ransac_pred, '-b', label='RANSAC regressor')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')

plt.xlabel('GDP')
plt.ylabel('Military Expenditure')
plt.title('Effect of GDP on military expenditure using RANSAC')
plt.show()

print('Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y, ransac_pred))
print('Coefficient of determination: %.2f'% r2_score(y, ransac_pred))

Mean squared error: 1161029260639288557568.00
Coefficient of determination: 0.62

From above regressions we do see that there is a positive relationship between GDP and Military Expenditure. Countries are more likely to spend more on military the more GDP they have.

Total military size per expenditure vs Expenditure¶

We know that military power is more than just head-count. With development of technology, military expenditure is more than just gearing up a solider. Its about developing and purchasing fighter jets, tanks, various equipments, welfare and more. Some even suggest that with modern warfare, number of soldier does not matter as much. If such is the case, we should see that as military expenditure grow, we should see less soldiers per expenditure as technology can replace headcount to a extent.

Interpretation: Drawing conclusions¶

We first saw that United States while spending exorbitant amount of money, ranked low in GPI Index.

I don't mean to sound idealistic and military forces are uncessary. For example, we saw that there is a positive relationship between GDP and military expenditure; that a country with More GDP spend more in military. This makes snese as the bigger the economy, more likely it is that the country is mroe active player in the global scene and thus are more likely to interact with other country and come across difference of interests. Military power will give upper hand in not only solving the conflict forcefully but give more power when solving diplomatically. Unless the world suddenly comes together and decides to have no violence whatsoever, military power is crucial to voicing and defending your interests.

However, as we have seen from the analysis, military expenditure, active military personel count all negatively impacts peace index. This can also be seen intuitively on our first bar graph where China, and United States that spend exorbitant amount on military both ranked low on GPI while top 5 countries spend very little. While military force may help defend or take upper hand in conflict, it negatively impacts peace. Therefore, in order to promote peace, more efforts than beyond keeping order thorugh military power needs to be done.
